  "summary": "Pausing the game does only pause the game Igt",
  "environment_raw": null,
  "description": "Pausing the game does only pause the game Igt n n",
  "Steps to Reproduce": "1. Launch Minecraft and enter a singleplayer world in either Creative or Survival mode.\n2. Begin gameplay by moving around and interacting with the environment.\n3. Press the Esc key to open the pause menu.\n4. Observe that the game pauses as intended, preventing player movement and interactions.\n5. While in the pause menu, wait for a few moments and note that the in-game time continues to progress in the background.\n6. Exit the pause menu by pressing the Esc key again.\n7. Confirm that the game resumes normally and that the in-game time reflects the progression that occurred while the game was paused.",
  "Environment": "Minecraft Java Edition Version 25w33a (snapshot)",
  "Observed Behavior": "When the player pauses the game using the default key (Esc), the game enters a pause state where all in-game actions are halted. However, this pause functionality only affects the local player's gameplay experience. In Java Edition, the game effectively freezes, preventing any movement from entities, including mobs, and halting environmental changes such as weather effects or block interactions. \n\nIn Bedrock Edition, the pause functionality behaves differently. While the game does pause for the individual player, it does not pause the game world for other players in a multiplayer environment. This means that if a player accesses the pause menu, other players can continue to interact with the world, including moving, mining, and engaging with mobs. \n\nFurthermore, in Bedrock Edition, certain game mechanics that should cease during a pause (like fire spread or mob movement) continue to function normally. This discrepancy in pause behavior between the two editions can lead to confusion, especially in multiplayer scenarios, as the paused player remains unaware of ongoing actions occurring around them. \n\nOverall, the pause function does not universally stop all game mechanics for all players, particularly in Bedrock Edition, where the game continues to operate in the background even when one player is paused.",
  "Expected Behavior": "When the game is paused by pressing the Esc key, all in-game actions should cease, allowing the player to access the pause menu without any time progression. This includes stopping the movement of mobs, preventing the spread of fire, and halting any environmental changes such as weather effects. The game should remain in a completely frozen state until the player chooses to resume gameplay, ensuring that no unintended actions occur during this time. This behavior aligns with the intended functionality of the pause feature as described in official Minecraft documentation.",
